{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511244"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:39:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:39:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11729"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11729"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.16,0.12,0.64,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104081"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4342"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"1480"},{"type":"tags","id":"2085"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44949"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104081"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents with a one-month history of persistent right ear pain. He does not have any deafness or discharge from that ear. His medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes. He has a 40-pack-year smoking history and drinks two cans of beer a day. Previous otoscopy revealed wax filling both external auditory canals, which was removed, but it did not resolve his earache. Follow up examination shows normal oral and aural findings, but rhinoscopy shows a deviated nasal septum and hypertrophied turbinates.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to help determine the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Orthopantomogram","Tympanometry","Laryngoscopy","CT sinuses","Pure tone audiometry"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are two types of otalgia (earache): primary and secondary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary otalgia\u003C/strong\u003E is ear pain that arises \u003Cstrong\u003Edirectly\u003C/strong\u003E from\u00a0pathology within the inner, middle, or external \u003Cstrong\u003Eear\u003C/strong\u003E.\u00a0 Secondary or referred otalgia is ear pain that occurs from pathology located outside the ear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOverall, primary causes tend to be more common. Men tend to have a primary cause, while women tend to have a secondary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEar infections, trauma, \u003Cstrong\u003Eimpacted wax\u003C/strong\u003E, growth inside any ear space, etc. are some common causes of \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary otalgia\u003C/strong\u003E. Temporal arteritis, \u003Cstrong\u003Esinusitis\u003C/strong\u003E, nasal polyps, nasopharyngeal malignancy, etc. are some causes of\u003Cstrong\u003E secondary otalgia\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the above scenario, the individual does not have any other primary ear complaints, including ear discharge and/or hearing loss, which gives suspicion of \u003Cstrong\u003Esecondary otalgia.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe long\u003Cstrong\u003E duration of pain, \u003C/strong\u003Ehistory of\u003Cstrong\u003E smoking, \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Erhinoscopy findings of a \u003Cstrong\u003Edeviated nasal septum \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E hypertrophied turbinate\u003C/strong\u003E suggest chronic rhinosinusitis. The best next step will be a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the sinuses\u003C/strong\u003E, which will show opacity, hyperostosis, and intrasinus calcification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrthopantomogram (OPG) \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be used to look for secondary causes of otalgia like odontogenic infection, abscessed maxillary molars eroding into the maxillary sinus and causing chronic sinusitis, temporomandibular joint degenerative diseases, etc. In the above scenario, in the absence of dental complaints and a normal oral exam, \u003Cstrong\u003ECT sinuses\u003C/strong\u003E would be of much higher yield as compared to OPG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETympanometry\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in the assessment of suspected or known disorders of the \u003Cstrong\u003Etympanic membrane\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Emiddle ear system\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehearing\u003C/strong\u003E. Findings in otoscopy and the tuning fork test cue you towards the need for tympanometry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaryngoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be advised if the patient had complaints of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehoarseness of voice\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edysphagia\u003C/strong\u003E along with his earache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPure-tone audiometry\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for determining the type, degree, and configuration of a hearing loss in patients, including the amount of conductive compared to sensorineural hearing loss, but in the above case, there is \u003Cstrong\u003Eno history of hearing loss.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first step in evaluating otalgia includes a comprehensive history and physical examination.","If the ear exam is normal and without an obvious cause of otalgia, then the next step is to perform a comprehensive evaluation for secondary causes which guides you to the need for lab or imaging studies."],"references":["Visvanathan V, Kelly G. 12 minute consultation: an evidence-based management of referred otalgia. Clin Otolaryngol. 2010 Oct;35(5):409-14.","Jaber JJ, Leonetti JP, Lawrason AE, Feustel PJ. Cervical spine causes for referred otalgia. Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2008 Apr;138(4):479-85.","Fenton JE, Uzomefuna V, O\u0027Rourke C, Kaare M. Applying the Ts of referred otalgia to a cohort of 226 patients. Clin Otolaryngol. 2018 Jun;43(3):937-940.","Earwood JS, Rogers TS, Rathjen NA. Ear Pain: Diagnosing Common and Uncommon Causes. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Jan 01;97(1):20-27.","Kim SH, Kim TH, Byun JY, Park MS, Yeo SG. Clinical Differences in Types of Otalgia. J Audiol Otol. 2015 Apr;19(1):34-8."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86400"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11729"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86400"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T12:24:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T12:24:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4342"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104081"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu